data.content:
Here are better MSTest assertions for your scenarios:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Instead of Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)
    Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0); // or use CollectionAssert below

    // Instead of Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive))
    CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(users);
    // For predicate checks, MSTest doesn't have a built-in "all match" —
    // keep Assert.IsTrue(users.All(...)) or check each:
    foreach (var u in users)
        Assert.IsTrue(u.IsActive, $"User {u.Name} is not active");

    // Instead of Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);

    // Instead of Assert.IsTrue(admin != null)
    var admin = users.Single(u => u.Role == "Admin");
    Assert.IsNotNull(admin);
}
```

**Key replacements:**

| Instead of | Use |
|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(x != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(x)` |
| `Assert.IsTrue(count == 3)` | `Assert.AreEqual(3, count)` |
| `Assert.IsTrue(list.Contains(x))` | `CollectionAssert.Contains(list, x)` |

**Other useful `CollectionAssert` methods:**
- `CollectionAssert.AreEqual(expected, actual)` — same order
- `CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expected, actual)` — any order
- `CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreUnique(collection)`
- `CollectionAssert.IsSubsetOf(subset, superset)`

The main benefit: better failure messages. `Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count)` tells you "expected 3 but got 5", while `Assert.IsTrue(...)` only says "expected true, got false."
